        "creation_date": 1223430838,
        "answer_count": 5,
        "title": "JUnit TestCase object instantiation",
        "body": "<p>Is a new (or different) instance of <code>TestCase<\/code> object is used to run each test method in a JUnit test case?  Or one instance is reused for all the tests?<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class MyTest extends TestCase {\n  public void testSomething() { ... }\n  public void testSomethingElse() { ... }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>While running this test, how many instances of <code>MyTest<\/code> class is created?<\/p>\n\n<p>If possible, provide a link to a document or source code where I can verify the behaviour.<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 181106,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "junit",
            "instantiation",
            "testcase"
        ],
        "score": 9,
        "accepted_answer_id": 181178,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 6073,
        "last_edit_date": 1280318687
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/bea5dab764a7a4945d874b9fecfc1802?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 6590,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 11142,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/11142/anjanb",
                "reputation": 14142,
                "display_name": "anjanb",
                "accept_rate": 49
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 8,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1223430943,
            "creation_date": 1223430943,
            "body": "<p>Yes, a separate instance is created.<\/p>\n\n<p>While running that test, 2 instances of MyTest gets created.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you want a different behavior, one option is to use a similar tool called TestNG(<a href=\"http://testng.org/doc/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://testng.org/doc/<\/a>).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 181111,
            "question_id": 181106
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/14ef739d471d306d7ff10fc0ccfd0120?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 13054,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 26010,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/26010/dov-wasserman",
                "reputation": 2682,
                "display_name": "Dov Wasserman"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1223434730,
            "creation_date": 1223434730,
            "body": "<p>I couldn't find a clear answer in the JUnit docs about your question, but the intent, as anjanb wrote, is that each test is independent of the others, so a new TestCase instance could be created for each test to be run.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you have expensive test setup (\"<em>fixtures<\/em>\") that you want to be shared across all test cases in a test class, you can use the <strong>@BeforeClass<\/strong> annotation on a static method to achieve this result: <a href=\"http://junit.sourceforge.net/javadoc_40/org/junit/BeforeClass.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://junit.sourceforge.net/javadoc_40/org/junit/BeforeClass.html<\/a>. Note however, that a new instance may still be created for each test, but that won't affect the static data your @BeforeTest method has initialized.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 181178,
            "question_id": 181106
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/q32V5.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 7701,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 13447,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/13447/olaf-kock",
                "reputation": 48253,
                "display_name": "Olaf Kock",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1223452770,
            "creation_date": 1223439161,
            "body": "<p>There's one instance for each test run. Try<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class MyTest extends TestCase {\n  public MyTest() { System.out.println(\"MyTest Constructor\");\n  public void setUp() { System.out.println(\"MyTest setUp\");\n  public void tearDown() { System.out.println(\"MyTest tearDown\");\n  public void testSomething() { System.out.println(\"MyTest testSomething\");\n  public void testSomethingElse() { System.out.println(\"MyTest testSomethingElse\");\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>The Sourcecode (including that to newer versions - your and my example is Junit 3) is on <a href=\"http://www.junit.org\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">http://www.junit.org<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 181311,
            "question_id": 181106,
            "last_edit_date": 1223452770
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/454734ff570997776f63cfdf0f5418f7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 8244,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 14749,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/14749/chris-noe",
                "reputation": 37381,
                "display_name": "Chris Noe",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1223431153,
            "creation_date": 1223431153,
            "body": "<p>If you are asking this because you are concerned about data being initialized and re-initialized in your constructor, be aware that the prescribed way to initialize your test cases data is via setUp() and tearDown() exclusively.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 181114,
            "question_id": 181106
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/35e2075811bfe23252bf2483b04f39aa?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
